Nowadays more and more mats (tensors) have dims larger than 2. The stack buffer size can be used in Mat is 2, i.e.
- `MatSize` : `int rows` `int cols`
- `MatStep` : `size_t buf[2]`
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/blob/fcfdd311ab7ad32ebb08dcde65c3adf2ea2ce099/modules/core/include/opencv2/core/mat.hpp#L587-L614
Thus if we want to create 4-dim mats (like NCHW), we have to malloc 4 `int` for `MatSize` and 4 `size_t` for `MatStep` on heap (maybe more due to memory alignment). And they belongs to `Mat`, no refcount based strategy can be used to reduce the memory overhead.
Maybe 5 is a proper choice, like PyTorch does.
``` cpp
#define C10_SIZES_AND_STRIDES_MAX_INLINE_SIZE 5

  size_t size_{1};
  union {
    int64_t* outOfLineStorage_;
    // NOLINTNEXTLINE(*c-array*)
    int64_t inlineStorage_[C10_SIZES_AND_STRIDES_MAX_INLINE_SIZE * 2]{};
  };
```
> https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/f65a564fa2477eee0cc77e89951d30be19aca42a/c10/core/impl/SizesAndStrides.h#L307-L312
What we need to do maybe adding 3 `int` in `MatSize` (change its location just after `cols` and delete/union `int* p`) and 3 `size_t` in `MatStep::buf` (`size_t buf[5]`, delete / union `size_t* p`), thus increase `sizeof(Mat)` 3×4+3×8-8-8+4=24 bytes (last 4 is the possible memory layout padding). And some more detailed checks...
Is this feature appropriate? If yes, should it be based 4.x or 5.x?

